":"1250","1260":"1260","Abt 1219":"about 1219","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1244":"1244","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","about 1246":"about 1246","about 1244":"about 1244","1308":"1308","1219":"1219","Wiggenhall, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Mary the Virgin, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Wiggenhall St. Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","Burial details unknown":"Unknown Island, Western Australia, Australia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Germund","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French   Germaine  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Germund</i>, composed of the elements <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’."],"variants":[{"name":"Germaine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel, Emile, Henri.","Altered form of French   Germain  .","French: from the feminine form of   Germain  . Compare   Germond  ."]},{"name":"Germundson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Germundsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Germund</i> (see   Germond  )."]}]},{"name":"Lucia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the old Roman given name <i>Lucius</i>, which is probably a derivative of Latin <i>lux</i> ‘light’. The girl's name is common in Italy and elsewhere, and is found as a learned, Latinate doublet of   Lucy   in England.  St Lucia  of Syracuse, who was martyred in  304 , was a very popular saint in the Middle Ages; she is often represented in medieval art as blinded and with her eyes on a platter, but the tradition that she had her eyes put out is probably based on nothing more than the association between light and eyes."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSum